{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2fc9f096-fcf1-473f-8a4a-6e2d0966765c","content":"Two things change with MTP (`UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner=true`):\n\n1. **VSTest `--filter` is replaced by `--treenode-filter`**\n2. **Syntax switches from property expressions to a glob + bracket notation**\n\nYour old filter:\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\nTranslates to:\n```\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/**/*IntegrationTests*[Category=Smoke]\"\n```\n\n**How it maps:**\n\n| VSTest concept | MTP tree-node equivalent |\n|---|---|\n| `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests` | `/**/*IntegrationTests*` (glob match on the test node path) |\n| `Category=Smoke` | `[Category=Smoke]` (trait filter in brackets) |\n| `&` (AND) | Combining path glob with `[...]` is implicit AND |\n\nThe `--` separates `dotnet test` args from MTP args. The path `/**/*IntegrationTests*` uses `**` to match any depth (assembly/namespace) and `*IntegrationTests*` to match the class name.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bf0c6a75-ae50-4885-9127-b17eb76b8a6c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is migrating from xUnit v2 (with VSTest) to xUnit v3 (with MTP - Microsoft Testing Platform). The key changes:\n\n1. **Filter syntax changes with MTP**: When `UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner` is true, `dotnet test` uses MTP instead of VSTest. The `--filter` option syntax changes.\n\n2. **Their old filter**: `--filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"`\n   - `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests` - FQN contains \"IntegrationTests\"\n   - `Category=Smoke` - Trait \"Category\" equals \"Smoke\"\n   - `&` - AND operator\n\nWith MTP, the filter syntax shifts entirely—`dotnet test --filter` works differently than with VSTest, and MTP introduces `--treenode-filter` which uses glob-style path patterns like `/**/*IntegrationTests*` instead of the property-based filtering they're used to.\n\nTo use MTP filters with `dotnet test`, I need to pass `--` to separate the MTP-specific arguments, then construct the tree-node filter with path-based matching and trait properties in brackets. So the command becomes something like passing a filter that matches any test with \"IntegrationTests\" in the path and the Smoke category trait together.","outputTokens":979,"requestId":"CFC7:335471:5C80C55:67C6390:69EC0F72"},"id":"87bb206b-a5c3-42ec-9ca3-905f239d758d","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:49:10.333Z","parentId":"7d4df89b-f25e-4fc9-a508-9e61df0bda2d"}
